## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three compounding bugs** that combine to create an ever-worsening leak. Here's a full breakdown.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Runs on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No dependency array — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
});
```

Without a second argument, `useEffect` fires after **every single render**. Each state update (`setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`) causes a re-render, which causes the effect to fire again, which registers **new** listeners on top of the old ones. Then *those* listeners fire and trigger more state updates. The cycle looks like this:

```
mount
  → effect runs → listeners #1 added
    → scroll event → setState × 3
      → render → effect runs → listeners #2 added
        → scroll event → setState × 3 (×2 listeners now!)
          → render → effect runs → listeners #3 added
            ...and so on, unboundedly
```

After navigating away and back a few times, you can easily have **hundreds of active scroll listeners** on `window`.

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Survive Unmount)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ❌ Nothing returned — no removeEventListener ever called
});
```

`useEffect` expects you to return a cleanup function if you register side effects. When the component unmounts (user navigates away), React calls that cleanup. Without it:

- Every listener registered during the component's lifetime **remains attached to `window`** indefinitely.
- Each listener holds a **closure** over the component's state setter functions and their surrounding scope. This prevents the JavaScript garbage collector from reclaiming that memory.
- The next time the user navigates back, a fresh set of listeners is layered on top of the zombie ones from before.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Can't Be Removed

```jsx
// ❌ New function object created on every call — can never be removed
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
```

`removeEventListener` works by reference equality. It must receive the **exact same function object** that was passed to `addEventListener`. An inline arrow function creates a brand-new object every time — so even if you tried to call `removeEventListener` with a similar-looking function, it would silently do nothing:

```js
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => console.log('a')); // ref A
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => console.log('a')); // ref B — NOT removed!
```

For cleanup to work, you must capture the function in a named variable and pass that exact reference to both `add` and `remove`.

---

## Bonus Bug #4 — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

Even ignoring the listener accumulation, the scroll handler captures `lastScrollY` from the render it was created in. Since `lastScrollY` is state (not a ref), once you fix the dependency array to `[]`, the handler will **always compare against the initial value `0`**, making direction detection permanently broken. The fix is to move `lastScrollY` into a `useRef`, which is mutable and always reflects the latest value without causing re-renders.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Immediately Visible

In development, React 18 Strict Mode intentionally **mounts → unmounts → remounts** every component on initial load. This is designed to simulate the fast-refresh/navigation lifecycle and expose exactly this class of bug:

```
[StrictMode Dev] mount → cleanup → remount
```

With the buggy code, even the first page load in dev immediately registers **two sets of listeners** (one from the first mount that was never cleaned up, one from the remount). You'll see in DevTools that a single scroll event fires the handler twice — a dead giveaway that something is wrong. In production (where Strict Mode's double-invoke doesn't happen), the bug still exists but takes longer to manifest.

---

## The Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // ✅ useRef instead of useState for lastScrollY:
    //    - Mutable without triggering re-renders
    //    - Always holds the latest value (no stale closure risk)
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named functions — the SAME reference is used for both
        //    addEventListener and removeEventListener
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY; // mutate ref directly, no re-render
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Cleanup function — called on unmount (and before each re-run if
        //    deps ever change). Removes the exact same function references.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // ✅ Empty array — effect runs ONCE on mount, cleans up on unmount

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Listeners multiply on every render | No dependency array — effect re-runs after every state update | Add `[]` as second argument to `useEffect` |
| Listeners survive unmount | No cleanup function returned from `useEffect` | Return `() => { removeEventListener(...) }` |
| `removeEventListener` silently fails | Anonymous arrow functions create new references each time | Declare named functions (`handleScroll`, `handleResize`) and reuse the same reference |
| Stale `lastScrollY` after adding `[]` | State captured in closure is frozen at time of effect creation | Move `lastScrollY` to `useRef` — always mutable, never stale |

The corrected component registers exactly **two listeners on mount**, removes **both on unmount**, and never accumulates additional listeners regardless of how many times the user navigates away and back.

